<chapter xml:id="ApproximationIntegral">
  <title>More Approximation Methods</title>
  <section xml:id="SECTIONGaussianDistribution">
    <title>The Gaussian Distribution</title>

    <p>
      Back in <xref ref="SECTIONAppDefInt"></xref>, where we mentioned
      that it is widely accepted that a person's IQ (intelligence
      quotient) is normally distributed with a mean of <m>100</m> and
      a standard deviation of 15.  We mentioned that it is also widely
      accepted that someone with an IQ of 140 or above is in the
      genius range and that the probability of a random person having
      an IQ less than or equal to 140 is given by
      
      <me>\frac{1}{15\sqrt{2}}\int^{140}_{x=-\infty
      }{e^{-\frac{1}{2}{\left(\frac{x-100}{15}\right)}^2}}\dx{x}\approx
      0.99617</me> 

      Using this measurement, someone is considered to be of
      <q>superior intelligence</q> if they have an IQ between 110 and
      120.  A reasonable question to ask is <q>what is the probability
      of a person chosen at random having an IQ score which is
      considered superior intelligence level?</q> Mathematically, this
      is given by the area of the blue region under the following
      bell<ndash/>shaped curve.
    </p>

    <image source="IC/BellCurveIQ.png" width="100%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>

    <!--   <m>\frac{}{\sqrt{}}{}^{\frac{}{}{\left(\frac{}{}\right)}}</me>\frac{}{\sqrt{}}{}^{\frac{}{}{\left(\frac{}{}\right)}}</m>\includegraphics*[width=6.44in, height=1.37in, trim=0.00in 1.67in 0.00in 0.56in]{image99} -->
    <!-- </p> -->

    <p>
      As we mentioned in <xref ref="EXERCISEDefineConvIndInt"></xref>, the
      equation of the curve may look strange, but it takes into
      account that the curve is centered at the mean of <m>100</m> and has a
      standard deviation of <m>15</m>.  It also has the property that the
      total area under the curve is equal to one so that the
      probability that a person's IQ falls between <m>-\infty </m> and
      <m>\infty </m> is one.  This bell<ndash/>shaped curve is called the
      Gaussian distribution in honor of 
      <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Gauss/" visual="/mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Gauss/">Karl Friedrich Gauss</url>
      (1777<ndash/>1855), who developed such a curve to determine the
      probability of errors in astronomical observations, though he
      was not the first to consider such a probability distribution.
      Nonetheless, the probability of a random person's IQ falling
      between 110 and 120 is given by <me>\frac{1}{15\sqrt{2\pi
      }}\int^{120}_{x=110}{e^{-\frac{1}{2}{\left(\frac{x-100}{15}\right)}^2}}\
      \dx{x}</me>
    </p>

    <p>
      As we mentioned before, computing this integral poses a problem,
      as none of the antidifferentiation techniques we learned can
      determine an antiderivative for
      <m>e^{-\frac{1}{2}{\left(\frac{x-100}{15}\right)}^2}</m>. In
      fact, the antiderivative of this cannot be written in any form
      utilizing the functions we are familiar with.
    </p>

    <p>
      One way to handle this in a statistics class is to use a
      substitution to simplify the integrand a bit.  We want the
      random variable <m>x</m> representing a person's IQ score to
      satisfy <me>110\le x\le 120</me> Manipulating this, we have

      <me>110-100\le x-100\le 120-100</me>
      <me>\frac{10}{15}\le \frac{x-100}{15}\le \frac{20}{15}</me>
      Setting <m>z=\frac{x-100}{15}</m>, we see that we want a value for
      <me>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\int^{\frac{4}{3}}_{z=\frac{2}{3}} e^{-{\frac{1}{2}z^2}}\dx{z}</me>
    </p>

    <p>
      The random variable <m>z</m> follows a standard normal
      distribution meaning that it has a normal distribution which
      has been <q>standardized</q> to have a mean of <m>0</m> and a
      standard deviation of <m>1</m>.  However, we still don't have any
      techniques for computing an antiderivative for
      <m>e^{-{\frac{1}{2}z}^2}</m>.  There are tables and computer
      programs which provide approximations for such <q><m>z</m>
      values.</q>  For example, using such approximation techniques,
      we can determine that 

      <me>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi
      }}\int^{\frac{4}{3}}_{z=\frac{2}{3}}{e^{-{\frac{1}{2}z}^2}dz}\approx
      .1627</me>

      But this still begs the question, <q>How was this
      approximation determined?</q>  There are many other integrands
      for which antiderivatives cannot be determined.  In this
      chapter, we will be exploring two such methods.  The first
      method is to replace the integrand <mdash/> in this case
      <m>e^{-{\frac{1}{2}z}^2}</m> <mdash/>  with a function which is more
      easily integrated, hoping we can keep control of how far off
      this approximation is.  The second is to actually replace the
      integral which is an infinite sum of infinitesimals with a
      finite sum of finite quantities.  Again, we will want to keep
      track of how close our approximation is.  Both approaches have
      their advantages and disadvantages.
    </p>
  </section>

</chapter>
